[
    {
        "content": "<p>In <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Order/WellFoundedSet.html#Set.isWF_iff_no_descending_seq\">https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Order/WellFoundedSet.html#Set.isWF_iff_no_descending_seq</a>, there is a <code>OrderDual.toDual</code> applied on <code>n</code>. Why is this needed?</p>",
        "id": 517314153,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1746929278
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It looks like it's been this way since mathlib3, from <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib3/commit/4b440bb0be61a13cb5b222c153b7d407b3bffa4c\">this commit</a></p>",
        "id": 517321182,
        "sender_full_name": "Matt Diamond",
        "timestamp": 1746936106
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is indeed unnecessary. The story here is that <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"302826\">Aaron Anderson</span>  introduced that lemma in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/6113\">!3#6113</a> with statement</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">is_wf_iff_no_descending_seq</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">is_wf</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↔</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">order_dual</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↪</span><span class=\"n\">o</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">¬</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">range</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Then <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"214703\">Yury G. Kudryashov</span> changed it to the current type-incorrect statement in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/11303\">!3#11303</a>, probably by replacing the <code>order_hom</code> with <code>strict_anti</code> but keeping the <code>order_dual</code></p>",
        "id": 517321298,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1746936185
    },
